text: hi everyone Anthony Fantino here
the Internet's busiest music nerd and
it's time for a review of the new trash
talk record no peace him I drink your
swag I drink it up trash talk is a West
Coast hardcore punk band this is their
latest full-length LP and they have had
a pretty steady stream of full-length
albums and EPS ever since they formed in
the mid-2000s a lot of the time
releasing these projects through what I
imagine is their label trash talk
collective occasionally on a release
here and they're releasing something in
tandem with another label but the most
recent deal that they have inked believe
it or not has been with Odd Future Wolf
Gang kill them all that Odd Future with
them trash talk has released their last
full-length LP this full-length LP and
this relationship is not just business
it is artistic as well with trash talk
collaborating with Odd Future performing
with them live and truthfully it makes
me glad to see new groups out there sort
of working to create this cultural
crossover between the hardcore
underground of rock music and hip hop
not that there weren't already groups in
the past like body count but trash talk
and odd future should at least be
congratulated for continuing this
tradition for the most part in my
opinion the cultural boundaries between
all of these genres are for the most
part arbitrary there's no reason that
people can't be slipping through each
one of them at their leisure and
enjoying them all plus I really love
that recent collab track these guys put
out with Flatbush zombies all in all
trash talk definitely seems like one of
the more well-connected groups and
hardcore music out there right now but
as far as modern hardcore music goes to
me it doesn't get more inconspicuous
than this new record the most surprising
things about this LP were the intro and
outro traction The Alchemist and the two
features from King cruel and wiki of Rat
King when it comes to straight-up Punk
tracks there isn't much about
trash-talks muddy guitar tone and sort
of muffled lead and gang vocals that
brings anything distinct or memorable to
the table never mind
original or refreshing trash-talk is way
too far away from breaching that border
to even consider it I could at least say
that the recording quality of the first
releases I heard from these guys like
Cydia and is now as well as that awake
EP that came out on true Panther sounds
back in 2011 at least the production
there was brighter it was heavier it was
more overpowering but listening to deep
cuts on this record like bodies tougher
this song to me not only has just a
forgettable riff but the recording
quality of the track and just the
performance of the song I feel like I'm
listening to a demo from a band with a
tenth of trash-talks experience there
are tracks like locked in skin as well
where I really feel like the the
muddiness of the vocals kind of kills
the track and then their tracks on here
that I actually hear the vocals like
leach but I kind of cringe at the lyrics
I mean I get the sentiment of the song
talking about somebody who is leaching
from you or someone who is a bit of a
poisonous person who you want away from
you but this story is just put so
plainly and so witless Lee that there's
really nothing there for me to connect
to the experience that the lyrics
describe there are tracks on here that
are decent like SOS one of the catchy ER

leads on this track too as well as the
whole one of the lead single type tracks
from this album where the guitar riff on
this thing rides a kind of weird groove
leaving a lot of space in the very fast
aggressive riff and I feel like because
of that unintentionally the vocals read
a little bit better which makes me
connect to their ferocity so much easier
however this winning streak doesn't
really keep up on the rest of the LP for
the most part I get songs that I feel
like they're not that bad but they're
not that fantastic either I definitely
give it to trash-talk for coming with

Tunes or personality in their corner on
this LP to me this record is
middle-of-the-road
hardcore it's hardcore for the sake of
